The United States is taking action to combat forced labor in Xinjiang, China. At the recent G7 Summit, the US and other leading democracies expressed their commitment to ensuring global supply chains are free from forced labor. The Biden-Harris administration is translating this commitment into action by holding those who engage in forced labor accountable and removing goods made with forced labor from US supply chains. The Department of Homeland Security's US Customs and Border Protection, the Department of Commerce, and the Department of Labor are all taking steps to enforce these measures. The US believes that state-sponsored forced labor in Xinjiang is a violation of human dignity and unfair economic practice. The abuses in Xinjiang go beyond forced labor and include sexual violence, forced detentions, and genocide. The US will not tolerate forced labor in its supply chains and aims to support clean energy supply chains that are free from forced labor. The US Customs and Border Pro